\description{
The workhorse map layer. Given a \code{mapgl} map and an \code{sf} polygon layer, it
colors features by \code{column}, then — unless you turn them off — adds a matching
legend, a hover tooltip, and a click popup. It picks sensible defaults from
the data so a one-liner looks right, while leaving every piece overridable.

Coloring adapts to the column:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Categorical} columns (factor/character) get one color per category. If
the column is the neighborhood typology \code{nt_conc}, the canonical Eviction
Research Network palette is used automatically (the same colors as
\code{\link[=nt_pal]{nt_pal()}}); otherwise an evenly-spaced qualitative palette is generated.
\item \strong{Numeric} columns are binned with the ERN sequential ramp
(yellow -> orange -> red -> purple). Use \code{type = "continuous"} for a smooth
interpolation instead, and \code{breaks}/\code{colors}/\code{labels} to take full control.
}

Small layers are embedded directly in the map; large ones can be served as
vector tiles — see \code{tiles}.
